init_text: When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the side effects are finally discovered.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The rest of the world was not as hesitant to take the drug, and many saw immortality as a chance for humanity to expand and achieve incredible things.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Doctors no longer had to worry about sicknesses and disease, they could now devote their time towards helping people.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: While the young celebrated their immortality, the old feared that they would be forgotten.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: They set their sights on new frontiers that would be impossible for a normal human lifetime.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The immortals were only prolonging the inevitable.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I was concerned with how the immortals would feel after living for hundreds of years, or even thousands.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The drug had robbed them of all senses, leaving them to a life where they were no longer human.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The immortals were now a burden, and the "Lost Generation" was stuck in between.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The immortals were now at the mercy of the "Lost Generation", for they needed help.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The immortals were not the picture of humanity, they were a nightmare.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The immortals were not living, they were merely existing in the world.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I had witnessed the downfall of humanity, and luckily for me, I was spared from the pain of loss.
